init_text: You're Barack Obama. 4 years into your retirement, you awake to find a letter with no return address on your bedside table. It reads "I hope you've had a chance to relax Barack...but pack your bags and call the number below. It's time to start the real job." Signed simply, "JFK."

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It may be to a government office, or perhaps overseas.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You call the number, and it connects you to JFK.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You realize that it would be very easy to fake a message from JFK, and that there is no way to prove that the message is actually from JFK

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: , but you have to admit it's a pretty good message.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: JFK is urging you to go down to the graysons' house.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: He says there will be a note waiting for you there.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You know that there is a graysons who lives somewhere in the town you live, but you've never been to his house.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: JFK says that you will know the house when you see it, and tells you to go there.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: When you finally bring yourself to ask, he says that he's been here for 4 years, and that if anyone else had found him, they would

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You get very good at chess.
